II. Basic Statistics

The following code summarizes the three datasets by counting their lines, characters in words, words and checking the average numbers of characters per word and words per line.

library(stringi)
b0 <- stri_stats_general(blogs)
b1 <- stri_stats_latex(blogs)
blog_stat <- as.integer(c(b0[1],b1[c(1,4)],b1[1]/b1[4],b1[4]/b0[1]))
n0 <- stri_stats_general(news)
n1 <- stri_stats_latex(news)
news_stat <- as.integer(c(n0[1],n1[c(1,4)],n1[1]/n1[4],n1[4]/n0[1]))
t0 <- stri_stats_general(twitter)
t1 <- stri_stats_latex(twitter)
twitter_stat <- as.integer(c(t0[1],t1[c(1,4)],t1[1]/t1[4],t1[4]/t0[1]))
all_stat <- rbind(blog_stat, news_stat, twitter_stat)
colnames(all_stat) <- c('Lines', 'CharsInWords', 'Words', 'CharsPerWord', 'WordsPerLine')
all_stat

As the result, all three datasets have similar word length, although blogs and news have longer lines.

III. Sampling, Cleanning and Tokenizing

Due to the large size of the datasets, I will sample 1% of the total, convert them into corpora, clean up the corpora and combine them. Here I will not focus on the difference between the three datasets but on what happens after stop words are removed.

library(tm)
## Loading required package: NLP
library(RWeka)
set.seed(1)
sample.corpus <- function(x) {
  sample_len <- length(x)
  result_corpus <- Corpus(VectorSource(x[sample(1:sample_len, sample_len/100, replace=FALSE)]))
  return(result_corpus)
}
bcorpus <- sample.corpus(blogs)
ncorpus <- sample.corpus(news)
tcorpus <- sample.corpus(twitter)
total_corpus <- c(bcorpus, ncorpus, tcorpus)

total_corpus <- tm_map(total_corpus, content_transformer(function(x) iconv(x, from="latin1", to="ASCII", sub="")))
#You've got to have the above line to remove non-ASCII chars, otherwise 'tolower' will throw an error; curiously this only happens in knitr but not in the console
total_corpus <- tm_map(total_corpus, content_transformer(tolower))
total_corpus <- tm_map(total_corpus, removePunctuation)
total_corpus <- tm_map(total_corpus, removeNumbers)
total_corpus <- tm_map(total_corpus, stripWhitespace)
trimmed_corpus <- tm_map(total_corpus, removeWords, stopwords('english'))

So now I have two corpora (total and trimmed) to work with. Next I will tokenize them into one-, two- and three-gram matices.

UnigramTokenizer <- function(x) NGramTokenizer(x, Weka_control(min = 1, max = 1))
BigramTokenizer  <- function(x) NGramTokenizer(x, Weka_control(min = 2, max = 2))
TrigramTokenizer <- function(x) NGramTokenizer(x, Weka_control(min = 3, max = 3))
total_uni <- TermDocumentMatrix(total_corpus, control=list(tokenize = UnigramTokenizer))
total_bi <- TermDocumentMatrix(total_corpus, control=list(tokenize = BigramTokenizer))
total_tri <- TermDocumentMatrix(total_corpus, control=list(tokenize = TrigramTokenizer))
trimmed_uni <- TermDocumentMatrix(trimmed_corpus, control=list(tokenize = UnigramTokenizer))
trimmed_bi <- TermDocumentMatrix(trimmed_corpus, control=list(tokenize = BigramTokenizer))
trimmed_tri <- TermDocumentMatrix(trimmed_corpus, control=list(tokenize = TrigramTokenizer))

So the top counted grams in each corpus are as follows:

library(slam)
library(ggplot2)
bartop <- function(x, top, gram, corpustype) {
  #x is the matrix, top is the number of top grams, gram is number of gram and corpustype is 'total' or 'trimmed'
  sum_count <- head(sort(row_sums(x), decreasing=TRUE),top)
  df <- data.frame(term=names(sum_count), count=sum_count)
  df$term <- reorder(df$term, df$count)
  ggplot(data=df, aes(x=term, y=count)) + geom_bar(stat='identity') + coord_flip() + ggtitle(paste(gram, '-gram cumulative count of ', corpustype, ' corpus', sep=''))
}
bartop(total_uni, 30, 1, 'total')

bartop(total_bi, 30, 2, 'total')

bartop(total_tri, 30, 3, 'total')

bartop(trimmed_uni, 30, 1, 'non-stop-words')

bartop(trimmed_bi, 30, 2, 'non-stop-words')

bartop(trimmed_tri, 30, 3, 'non-stop-words')

It is not surprising to see high counts of stop words in the total corpus. However, the corpus without stop words does have some interesting patterns.
